<a href="javascript:card_browser(86)">Moria Scout</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(72)">Goblin Runner</a> x4<br>
Goblin Scavenger x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(82)">Host of Thousands</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(91)">They Are Coming</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(90)">Relics of Moria</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(78)">Goblin Swarms</a> x2<br>
Goblin <a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a>y x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(75)">Goblin Scimitar</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(85)">Moria Axe</a><br>
Cave Trolls Hammer<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> PLEASE READ STRATEGY BEFORE REVIEWING<br>
<br>
My first good deck was a Gandalf deck with an Arwen + Legolas start and a Nazgul shadow.  As I envisioned this, I revisited that idea and asked myself, Self, how good can I make a Gandalf fellowship with 40 cards?  Well, what you see is the result . . . <br>
<br>
Now, you must understand that all of my tournament decks are built on an underlying principle, a theory as it were, and in this deck that principle is that if I can play more counters to my opponents strategy than my opponent can to mine (i.e., if I play more cards), I will have an advantaged fellowship.  Of course, thats only viable if you have an engine that enables you to play those cards . . . hence my Moria shadow.  Furthermore, Moria not only empowers my fellowship, it also applies pressure when it counts most . . . from sites 4 through 6.<br>
<br>
That said, how does this deck beat you?  It beats you by going first and moving quickly because of a marked disparity in card advantage between your deck and mine.  Meanwhile, the shadow side is swarming and slowing down my opponent when possible, but its primary function is to move cards so that I can see more of my fellowship.  As a result, I get to site 9 first.<br>
<br>
Well, now that you understand the strategy, lets take a look at a couple of the less transparent card choices . . . <br>
<br>
Frodo, Son of Drogo<br>
Unless youve played the deck or seen it played, you cannot criticize this choice.  Reluctant Adventurer and Old Bilbos Heir just arent as useful as Son of Drogo.  A free Sting is nothing compared to the incredible amount of wound management that Son of Drogo affords me AND Son of Drogo mitigates the risk of Twilight Nazgul and Isengard Orcs.  He allows me to free up vitality for Filibert Bolger or Sting.  He turns extra copies of Gandalf into possible Frodo healers.  Also, Son of Drogo turns Strength of Spirit into an everything-card.  <br>
<br>
Strength of Spirit<br>
This is my everything card.  It adds to power (Gimli, Boromir, or Merry), blocks a minion (Rareagorn), reduces twilight (Glamdring or Sting), removes Burdens (Son of Hamfast), wounds minions (Aragorns Bow and Legolas), and it heals companions, thanks to the Frodo Signet.  It even juliennes fries.<br>
<br>
Filibert Bolger<br>
If you dont know the power of Filibert Bolger, let me explain.  The ability to cancel a fierce skirmish means that your opponent has to overwhelm you in the first round of skirmishes.  Thats pretty obvious, but not enough people recognize how powerful an ability that is.  It means that, in order for your opponent to overwhelm you, he will have to get more companions out than you have blockers for.  Otherwise, youll just cancel the second round.  Thus, with Son of Drogo and Ranger of the North, Filibert Bolger is the I Win Card.  <br>
<br>
Narya<br>
Originally, Narya was an additional copy of Gandalfs Staff, but then I realized what really was important was the extra vitality.  And in that respect, Narya shines.  Plus, it gives me another means of condition removal.<br>
<br>
Goblin Scrabbler/Goblin Warrior/Goblin Sneaks<br>
Discard decks are becoming a threat.  With these cards added into my deck, I can combat my opponents discard engines.  The most dangerous discard engines are Greatest Kingdom and White Arrows.  Hence, the Warrior and Scrabbler!  So, I absorb some discarding, which will get me to my Warrior/Scrabbler, and then I cancel the source.  Meanwhile, I have Sneaks recycling my minions to maintain my decks longevity.  Additionally, this package takes care of Shoulder Fire, Dwarven Tales, and Thrarin, while also combating the danger of the God Draws effect on throughput.  However, I will usually average 10 to 20 cards left in my draw deck at the end of the game.  For that reason, you could pull the Sneaks if you really want to.<br>
<br>
Why no Trust Me As You Once Did?<br>
Sleep Caradhras kills it.  I dont want to be killing my own conditions.<br>
<br>
Why Weathertop?<br>
Because you wont see it!  If you do, it means that your opponent has outbid you and went first.  In that situation, you need a means to slow them down.  Weathertop does that in a couple of ways.  First, it gives you twilight so you can play your shadow hand.  Second, it puts the question of Nazgul in your opponents head.  Hopefully, together, those factors will make your opponent stop so you can double into the lead. <br>
<br>
How to Play It<br>
<br>
Bid 5 (or more if youre daring) to go first.  Pull Sam.  Exhaust Sam.  If you have more companions in hand, play them.  However, 6 companions is bad.  7, 8, or 9 are okay because Enquea should only be able to kill 1 companion, so he cant do that much damage.  But with 6 companions, you give your opponent the opportunity to kill a companion of their choosing and leave you with weakly defended ring-bearer.  Its a dangerous situation; hence the unlucky number is 6.  Double move whenever appropriate.  Typically, I move 1-3, 3-4, 4-6, 6-8, and 8-9.  But that is sometimes subject to change depending on the situation.  During your shadow turns, play as many cards as you can.  Remember, your goal is not primarily to overwhelm (although its great if you can).  You just want to move cards and slow down your opponent if possible.  A Cave Troll-Balrog combo from 4 to 5 or 5 to 6 will help a great deal towards that end.  By defining the pace of the game, youre going to win half of your games by reaching site 9 and half of your games with overwhelms . . . but the bottom line is that youre winning.<br>
<br>
Some Things To Be Aware Of<br>
<br>
Early Game Weakness<br>
This deck is 80 cards.  As such, the statistics for your first couple of turns bring with them a great deal of uncertainty.  It is not inconceivable that you will run into some major problems before the first sanctuary.  However, remember that this deck is designed in such a way that you can absorb the losses of some seemingly game-breaking cards and still be in control.  So, if you get either a Gandalf or Gondor clog without the companions, dont be afraid to discard those cards.  The key to this deck is to get the cards moving.  As long as you can get the throughput working for you, youll be fine.  There is also another form of Early Game Weakness but it is for the shadow side.  Moria minions are just not effective at the early sites.  Barring a Cave Troll at the first couple of sites.  My Moria will never stop an opposing fellowship from doubling.  Again, remember, it is all about getting the cards to start moving.  Play the cards anyway, and youll be fine.<br>
<br>
Increased Opponent Efficiency<br>
This deck gives away a ton of twilight.  As a result, your opponents decks will play as they were meant to play.  They will have the twilight to clear their hands.  Therefore, they will be drawing more cards and playing more.  Thus, your opponents decks will be more effective.  Still, despite that increase in efficacy, the fellowship rolls and the Moria will swarm.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I only bring them up because no deck is perfect.  So, if you acknowledge these small holes and accept them they will not betray you.  Theyll just hang around and make things interesting.  Still, be aware and plan for them.  But all things considered, those holes are miniscule when compared to the strengths of this deck.  The Card Advantage is just too powerful to overcome.  Try it for yourself, sometime.  I think youll see.<br>
<br>
Anyway, thats the deck.  Enjoy!<br>
<br>
Devon This space intentionally left blank Clark<br>
